        "## 18.24 Common mistakes\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **Reporting only RMSE.** RMSE says little about uncertainty calibration.\n",
        "2. **Using confidence intervals instead of prediction intervals.** Prediction intervals must include future observation noise.\n",
        "3. **Random calibration split.** This can leak future regimes into calibration.\n",
        "4. **Ignoring horizon.** Coverage often deteriorates at longer horizons.\n",
        "5. **Assuming Gaussian residuals without checking.** Heavy tails and skewness matter for intervals.\n",
        "6. **Using training residuals for calibration.** Training residuals are often too optimistic.\n",
        "7. **Forgetting exogenous uncertainty.** Future covariates may themselves need forecasts.\n",
        "8. **Ignoring heteroskedasticity.** Constant-width intervals fail when uncertainty changes with level, season, or regime.\n",
        "9. **Overtrusting ensemble spread.** Ensemble spread is not the same as total predictive uncertainty.\n",
        "10. **Not connecting uncertainty to decisions.** A 90% interval may not be the right object for an asymmetric-cost problem.\n",
